Notes for Interactive Data Visualization with plotly in R augmented with perplexity.ai

Introduction

Core Concepts

Overview of plotly

The plotly R package serves as an interface to the plotly JavaScript graphing library, enabling the creation of interactive web-based graphics in R. Its popularity is evidenced by download rates significantly higher than competitors like rbokeh and highcharter as of November 2018.

Static vs. Interactive Visualization

Interactive graphics offer distinct advantages over static visualizations:

  • Static plots remain fixed and only display creator-highlighted information
  • Interactive plots allow users to:
    • Access hover information
    • Select/deselect data groups
    • Drill down to specific observations

Implementation Approaches

ggplot2 to plotly Conversion

A ggplot2 visualization requires three key components:

# 1. Dataset specification
static_plot <- wine %>% ggplot(
# 2. Aesthetic mappings
aes(x = Flavanoids, y = Proline, color = Type)
 ) +

# 3. Geometry specification
geom_point()

static_plot

Direct plotly Creation

Converting ggplot2 to plotly is straightforward:

ggplotly(static_plot)

Best Practices

Important Considerations

  • Interactivity alone doesn’t guarantee effective visualization
  • Focus on fundamental visualization design principles
  • Not all ggplot objects can be converted to plotly, making direct plotly creation skills valuable

Example Dataset

The course uses the wine dataset from UCI Machine Learning Repository, featuring: - 178 wine samples - Chemical analysis results - Three different Italian cultivars

Exercise

Converting a ggplot2 scatterplot

The ggplotly() command makes it easy to create interactive versions of most static plots created using the ggplot2 package. In this exercise, your task is to create an interactive version of the below scatterplot, exploring the relationship between video game sales in North America (NA_Sales) and aggregate critic score (Critic_Score) in 2016.

After creating the interactive graphic, be sure to explore what interactions are possible.

Note: loading plotly also loads ggplot2 and dplyr.

  • Load plotly.
  • Create a scatterplot with NA_Sales on the x-axis and Critic_Score on the y-axis for video games found in the vgsales dataset from 2016. Store this plot in the scatter object.
  • Use the ggplotly() command to convert scatter to a plotly interactive graphic.
# Store the scatterplot of Critic_Score vs. NA_Sales sales in 2016
scatter <- vgsales %>%
            filter(Year == 2016) %>%
            ggplot(aes(x = NA_Sales, y = Critic_Score)) +
            geom_point(alpha = 0.3)
# Convert the scatterplot to a plotly graphic
ggplotly(scatter)

Univariate graphics

Univariate Visualization in plotly The lesson focuses on creating standalone plotly visualizations for single variables, specifically through: - Bar charts for categorical data - Histograms for continuous data

Implementation Patterns

Basic plotly Structure

Every plotly visualization consists of three fundamental components:

# 1. Dataset specification
data %>% plot_ly()

# 2. Aesthetic mappings using tildes
x = ~variable_name

# 3. Trace specification (plot type)
%>% add_bars()  # or add_histogram()

Bar Chart Creation

# Basic bar chart
wine %>%
  count(Type) %>%
  plot_ly(x = ~Type, y = ~n) %>%
  add_bars()
# Ordered bar chart
wine %>%
  count(Type) %>%
  mutate(Type = fct_reorder(Type, n, .desc = TRUE)) %>%
  plot_ly(x = ~Type, y = ~n) %>%
  add_bars()

Histogram Implementation

# Basic histogram
wine %>%
  plot_ly(x = ~Phenols) %>%
  add_histogram()
# Customized bins
wine %>%
  plot_ly(x = ~Phenols) %>%
  add_histogram(nbinsx = 10)  # Specify number of bins
# or

wine %>%
  plot_ly(x = ~Phenols) %>%
  add_histogram(xbins = list(start = 0.8, end = 4, size = 0.25))  # Specify bin parameters

Best Practices

Histogram Binning

  • Explore different binning schemes
  • Avoid bins that are too wide (mask features)
  • Avoid bins that are too narrow (provide little insight)
  • Check variable summary before setting custom bin parameters

Knowledge Check

  1. What are the three fundamental components of a plotly visualization?
    • Dataset specification
    • Aesthetic mappings with tildes
    • Trace specification
  2. How can you improve bar chart readability?
    • Reorder bars using fct_reorder
    • Consider descending/ascending order
    • Use appropriate bin widths for histograms

Bivariate graphics

Core Concepts

Bivariate Visualization Types

The lesson covers three main types of bivariate plots in plotly:

  1. Scatterplots (numeric vs. numeric)
  2. Stacked bar charts (categorical vs. categorical)
  3. Boxplots (categorical vs. numeric)

Implementation Patterns

Scatterplot Creation

# Basic scatterplot
winequality %>%
  plot_ly(x = ~residual_sugar, 
          y = ~fixed_acidity) %>%
  add_markers()
Warning: Ignoring 12 observations

Stacked Bar Charts

# Counts
winequality %>%
  count(type, quality_label) %>%
  plot_ly(x = ~type, 
          y = ~n, 
          color = ~quality_label) %>%
  add_bars() %>%
  layout(barmode = "stack")
# Proportions
winequality %>%
  count(type, quality_label) %>%
  group_by(type) %>%
  mutate(prop = n/sum(n)) %>%
  plot_ly(x = ~type, 
          y = ~prop, 
          color = ~quality_label) %>%
  add_bars() %>%
  layout(barmode = "stack")

Boxplot Implementation

winequality %>%
  plot_ly(x = ~quality_label, 
          y = ~alcohol) %>%
  add_boxplot()

Best Practices

Visualization Selection - Use scatterplots for exploring relationships between continuous variables - Choose stacked bar charts for categorical variable associations - Apply boxplots to examine numeric distribution across categories

Data Representation - Consider whether counts or proportions better serve your analysis goals - Use grouping and data manipulation to prepare data appropriately - Pay attention to layout specifications for proper visualization

Knowledge Check

  1. Which plot type would you use to explore:
    • Relationship between sugar content and acidity? (Scatterplot)
    • Distribution of quality across wine types? (Stacked bar chart)
    • Alcohol content variation by quality level? (Boxplot)
  2. How do you convert a regular bar chart to a stacked bar chart in plotly?
    • Add layout(barmode = “stack”)
    • Group data appropriately
    • Consider whether to use counts or proportions

Customizing traces

Core Concepts

In this lesson, you learn how to customize traces in plotly to enhance the appearance of your visualizations, making them ready for publication. Specifically, the lesson covers how to adjust colors, opacity, symbols, and other marker options in your plots.

Implementation Patterns

Color Customization

To change the color of markers in a trace (e.g., bars in a histogram), you can use the color argument. By default, plotly assumes you’re mapping a variable to color, but if you want to set a static color (e.g., red), you need to use the I() function:

# Change histogram color to red
winequality %>%
  plot_ly(x = ~fixed_acidity) %>%
  add_histogram(color = I("red"))

Opacity Adjustment

Overplotting can make scatterplots difficult to interpret. One solution is to adjust the opacity of the points:

# Set opacity to 20% (80% transparency)
winequality %>%
  plot_ly(x = ~residual_sugar, y = ~fixed_acidity) %>%
  add_markers(marker = list(opacity = 0.2))

This makes high-density areas appear darker, helping reveal patterns in overlapping data points.

Symbol Customization

Another way to address overplotting is by changing the plotting symbols. For example, using open circles instead of filled ones:

# Use open circle symbols
winequality %>%
  plot_ly(x = ~residual_sugar, y = ~fixed_acidity) %>%
  add_markers(marker = list(symbol = "circle-open"))

Other Marker Options

You can also customize other marker properties:

  • Size: Adjust the size of scatterplot points.
  • Width: Modify the width of lines dividing bars in histograms or bar charts.

Exercise

Color and opacity

Increasing the transparency (i.e. decreasing the opacity) of a trace can help improve its readability. For example, if there are bars of similar heights in bar charts or histograms, increasing the transparency enables one to see the horizontal grid lines behind the bars, making judgement of relative heights easier. Of course, the hover info can clarify this, but why not make it as easy as possible for your reader?

In this exercise, you will adapt plotly code to change the color of a histogram and increase its transparency.

plotly has already been loaded for you.

  • Adapt the code so that the bars of the histogram are "navy" and are 50% transparent.
# Create a histogram of Critic_Score with navy bars that are 50% transparent
vgsales2016 %>%
  plot_ly(x = ~Critic_Score) %>%
  add_histogram(color = I("navy"), opacity = 0.5)
Warning: Ignoring 270 observations

Alternative color formats

R has a large number of named colors, but sometimes you need a color that isn’t named. For example, what if your organization’s specific shade of blue is somewhere between "navy" and "dodgerblue4"? Luckily, plotly allows you to specify colors using other formats, including RGB, RGBA, HEX, HCL, HSL, and HSV.

In this exercise, you will change the histogram’s color to using HEX and RGB formats.

Note that plotly has already been loaded for you.

Use the as is function to set the color of the histogram to #111e6c.

# Change the color of the histogram using a hex code
vgsales2016 %>%
  plot_ly(x = ~Critic_Score) %>%
  add_histogram(color=I('#111e6c'))
Warning: Ignoring 270 observations

Set the histogram color to "rgb(17, 30, 108)" via the marker argument.

# Change the color of the histogram using rgb()
vgsales2016 %>%
  plot_ly(x = ~Critic_Score) %>%
  add_histogram(marker = list(color = I("rgb(17, 30, 108")))
Warning: Ignoring 270 observations

Size and symbol

To change the default size and shape of points on a scatterplot or boxplot, we pass the marker argument a list with the size and symbol arguments. As you have seen, changing the plotting symbol can make charts easier to read by addressing issues such as overplotting. Decreasing the size of points can also help overcome minor overplotting issues—just don’t make the points hard to see!

  • Change the plotting symbol to a diamond and decrease its size to 4.
# Set the plotting symbol to diamond and the size to 4
plot_ly(data = vg2016, x = ~User_Score, y = ~Critic_Score) %>% 
    add_markers(marker = list(symbol = I('diamond'), size = 4)) 
Warning: Ignoring 270 observations

Color Usage in plotly

Implementation Patterns

Adding Color for Categorical Variables

# Map wine type to color
wine %>%
  plot_ly(x = ~Flavanoids, 
          y = ~Alcohol, 
          color = ~Type) %>%
  add_markers()

Representing Quantitative Variables with Color

# Color gradient for numeric variable
wine %>%
  plot_ly(x = ~Flavanoids, 
          y = ~Alcohol, 
          color = ~Color) %>%
  add_markers()

Customizing Color Palettes

# Using RColorBrewer palette
wine %>%
  plot_ly(x = ~Flavanoids, 
          y = ~Alcohol, 
          color = ~Type) %>%
  add_markers(colors = "Dark2")
# Manual color specification
wine %>%
  plot_ly(x = ~Flavanoids, 
          y = ~Alcohol, 
          color = ~Type) %>%
  add_markers(colors = c("orange", "black", "skyblue"))

Best Practices

Color Selection - Use discrete colors for categorical variables - Apply color gradients for continuous variables - Consider colorblind-safe palettes - Match website or organizational themes when needed

Important Distinctions - Setting static colors: Use I() function - Changing color palettes: Specify vector of colors - Consider data type (factor vs. numeric) for appropriate color mapping

Practical Applications

Revealing Patterns - Color can explain apparent nonlinear relationships by revealing group differences - Color gradients can show relationships with a third numeric variable - Different wine types showed distinct relationships between alcohol and flavanoids

Knowledge Check

  1. How do you distinguish between:
    • Setting a static color for all points?
    • Defining a color palette for groups?
  2. What are the two main ways to customize color palettes in plotly?
    • Using RColorBrewer palettes
    • Manually specifying colors
  3. When might you need to convert a numeric variable to a factor?
    • When you want discrete colors instead of a gradient
    • When the numeric values represent categories

Beyond color: Symbols

Using both color and shape to encode a categorical variable can be a useful strategy to reveal relationships more effectively. This double-encoding strategy uses two pre-attentive visual cues to more-quickly communicate information to the reader. This idea is implemented by default in plotly; if you map a variable to the symbol, plotly automatically maps the variable to the color.

To map a variable to the plotting shape, add a symbol argument to the plot_ly() command.

Caution: It is poor practice to use color and shape to communicate different variables, since the two features have been shown to interfere with each other, making it more difficult to distinguish either variable.

  • Use the vgsales2016 data frame to create a scatterplot with Critic_Score on the x-axis and User_Score on the y-axis where the plotting symbol represents a game’s Rating.
# Create a scatterplot of User_Score against Critic_Score coded by Rating
vgsales2016 %>%
   plot_ly(x = ~Critic_Score, y = ~ User_Score) %>%
   add_markers(symbol = ~Rating)

Hover Information in plotly

Implementation Patterns

Default Hover Behavior

Different plot types show different default information:

  • Scatterplots: Show coordinate pairs
  • Bar charts: Display bar heights
  • Boxplots: Show category name and summary statistics (min, Q1, median, Q3, max)

Modifying Hover Information

# Basic hover info modification
wine %>%
  count(Type) %>%
  plot_ly(x = ~Type, 
          y = ~n,
          hoverinfo = "y") %>%
  add_bars()

Available hoverinfo Options:

  • “all” (default)
  • “x”
  • “y”
  • “none”
  • “x+y”
  • “x+y+z”

Custom Hover Text

# Creating custom hover labels
wine %>%
  plot_ly(x = ~Flavanoids, 
          y = ~Alcohol,
          hoverinfo = "text",
          text = ~paste("Flavanoids:", Flavanoids, "<br>",
                       "Alcohol:", Alcohol)) %>%
  add_markers()

Best Practices

Hover Text Construction

  • Use meaningful variable labels
  • Include units where appropriate
  • Use HTML line breaks (<br>) for multi-line text
  • Remember to use the tilde (~) operator for column mapping

Information Display

  • Choose appropriate level of detail
  • Consider removing redundant information
  • Make labels clear and intuitive
  • Format numbers appropriately

Technical Notes

Important Syntax Elements

  • Use paste() for combining text and values
  • Include ~ before paste() to properly map columns
  • Use HTML tags for formatting
  • Set hoverinfo = "text" for custom text display

Layout Customization in plotly

The layout() function serves as the primary tool for customizing plot elements, similar to combining labs() and theme() in ggplot2. It allows customization of:

  • Axes
  • Legend
  • Canvas
  • Plot size

Implementation Patterns

Axis Labels and Titles

# Basic axis labeling
winequality %>%
  plot_ly(x = ~free_so2, y = ~total_so2) %>%
  add_markers(marker = list(opacity = 0.2)) %>%
  layout(
    xaxis = list(title = "Free SO2 (ppm)"),
    yaxis = list(title = "Total SO2 (ppm)"),
    title = "Does free SO2 predict total SO2 in wine?"
  )

Axis Transformations

# Log transformation example
winequality %>%
  plot_ly(x = ~free_so2, y = ~total_so2) %>%
  add_markers(marker = list(opacity = 0.2)) %>%
  layout(
    xaxis = list(
      title = "Free SO2 (ppm, log scale)",
      type = "log"
    ),
    yaxis = list(
      title = "Total SO2 (ppm, log scale)",
      type = "log"
    )
  )

Grid Customization

# Removing grid lines and zero lines
winequality %>%
  plot_ly(x = ~free_so2, y = ~total_so2) %>%
  add_markers(marker = list(opacity = 0.5)) %>%
  layout(
    xaxis = list(
      zeroline = FALSE
    ),
    yaxis = list(
      zeroline = FALSE,
      showgrid = FALSE
    )
  )

Canvas Customization

# Modifying background colors
winequality %>%
  plot_ly(x = ~free_so2, y = ~total_so2) %>%
  add_markers(marker = list(opacity = 0.5)) %>%
  layout(
    plot_bgcolor = toRGB("gray90"),
    paper_bgcolor = toRGB("skyblue")
  )

Best Practices

Layout Considerations

  • Use clear, informative axis labels with units
  • Apply appropriate axis transformations when needed
  • Consider removing unnecessary grid lines
  • Choose background colors that enhance readability

Color Management

  • Use toRGB() function for R colors
  • Direct hex codes are also supported
  • Consider contrast between plot elements and background

Layering in plotly

The lesson focuses on creating complex visualizations by combining multiple traces, specifically: - Adding smoothers to scatterplots - Overlaying density plots - Comparing multiple models

Implementation Patterns

Adding LOESS Smoother

# Fit LOESS model
m <- loess(Alcohol ~ Flavanoids, data = wine)

# Create layered plot
wine %>%
  plot_ly(x = ~Flavanoids, y = ~Alcohol) %>%
  add_markers(showlegend = FALSE) %>%
  add_lines(y = ~fitted(m), showlegend = FALSE)

Comparing Multiple Models

# Fit models
m <- loess(Alcohol ~ Flavanoids, data = wine)
m2 <- lm(Alcohol ~ poly(Flavanoids, 2), data = wine)

# Create comparison plot
wine %>%
  plot_ly(x = ~Flavanoids, y = ~Alcohol) %>%
  add_markers(showlegend = FALSE) %>%
  add_lines(y = ~fitted(m), name = "LOESS") %>%
  add_lines(y = ~fitted(m2), name = "Polynomial")

Density Plot Overlays

# Calculate densities for each wine type
d1 <- density(wine %>% filter(Type == 1) %>% pull(Flavanoids))
d2 <- density(wine %>% filter(Type == 2) %>% pull(Flavanoids))
d3 <- density(wine %>% filter(Type == 3) %>% pull(Flavanoids))

# Create layered density plot
plot_ly() %>%
  add_lines(x = ~d1$x, y = ~d1$y, name = "Type1") %>%
  add_lines(x = ~d2$x, y = ~d2$y, name = "Type2") %>%
  add_lines(x = ~d3$x, y = ~d3$y, name = "Type3")

Best Practices

Design Considerations

  • Choose the simplest visualization that effectively communicates your message
  • Layer traces thoughtfully to avoid visual clutter
  • Use legends appropriately to distinguish between traces
  • Consider removing unnecessary legend entries

Technical Tips

  • Base layer aesthetics are inherited by subsequent layers
  • Use showlegend = FALSE to hide specific traces from the legend
  • Name traces meaningfully when including multiple models or groups

Dataset Context

The examples use the wine dataset containing:

  • 13 chemical measurements
  • Three wine types
  • Variables including Flavanoids, Alcohol content

Adding a linear smoother

You’ve seen how to add LOESS smoothers to a scatterplot by using both the add_markers() and add_lines() traces. Adding a linear smoother uses the same approach, but you use lm() command to fit the linear model.

In this exercise, your task is to add a linear smoother to a scatterplot of user score against critic score for video games in 2016.

When you add smoothers, missing values (NAs) can be problematic because many modeling functions automatically delete missing observations. To avoid this conflict, use select() and na.omit() to delete observations before plotting.

Note that plotly and the vgsales2016 data has already been loaded for you.

  • Fit a linear regression model using Critic_Score as the predictor variable and User_Score as the response variable. Store this model in the object m.
  • Create a scatterplot showing Critic_Score on the x-axis and User_Score on the y-axis.
  • Add a linear smoother to your scatterplot representing the fitted values.
# Fit the regression model of User_Score on Critic_Score
m <- lm(User_Score ~ Critic_Score, data = vgsales2016 %>% filter(User_Score != 'tbd'),
        na.action = na.omit)
# Create the scatterplot with smoother
vgsales2016 %>% filter(User_Score != 'tbd' & !is.na(User_Score)) %>%
   select(User_Score, Critic_Score) %>%
   na.omit() %>%
   plot_ly(x = ~Critic_Score, y = ~User_Score) %>%
   add_markers(showlegend = FALSE) %>%
   add_lines(y = ~fitted(m))

Overlayed density plots

In this exercise, you will learn how to create density plots and overlay them to compare the distribution of critic scores for three video game publishers: Activision, Electronic Arts, and Nintendo.

To create a density plot for Critic_Score, store the results of the density() command, and then pass the x and y coordinates to add_lines():

    d <- density(vgsales2016$Critic_Score, na.rm = TRUE)
    plot_ly() %>%
      add_lines(x = ~d$x, y = ~d$y, fill = 'tozeroy') %>%
      layout(xaxis = list(title = 'Critic score'),
             yaxis = list(title = 'Density'))

Notice how you can create new plot types easily using familiar code! The fill = 'tozeroy' argument fills the area under the curve.

Data frames activision,ea, and nintendo are loaded, as is plotly.

  • Compute density curves of Critic_Score for Activision, EA, and Nintendo, storing them in the d.a, d.e, and d.n objects, respectively.

ea <- vgsales2016 %>% filter(Publisher == "Electronic Arts")

plot_ly() %>%

  layout(xaxis = list(title = 'Critic Score'),
         yaxis = list(title = 'Density'))

Automated faceting

In the previous exercise, you manually create a faceted scatterplot. This was not very tedious because you were only focused on two groups. However, there are 6 platforms in the vgsales2016 dataset, and it would be very tedious to manually code 6 scatterplots.

In this exercise, you will practice using group_by(), nest(), mutate(), and map2() to automate the process of creating a faceted scatterplot using the following template:

    data %>%
      group_by(factor) %>%
      nest() %>%
      mutate(
          plot = map2(data, factor,
            \(data, factor) 
                plot_ly(data = data, x = ~x, y = ~y) %>%
                      add_markers(name = ~factor)
        )) %>%
      subplot(nrows = R, shareY = TRUE, shareX = TRUE)

Plot and axis titles

In the previous two exercises, you saw a set of subplots that lack any axis labels and a set of subplots that used the column names as axis labels. Why are they different? By default, the subplot() command sets titleX = shareX and titleY = shareY; thus, axis labels are only displayed if shareX and/or shareY are TRUE. You can add titleX = TRUE and/or titleY = TRUE to override this behavior.

In this example, your task is to add titles to subplots. Note that plotly has already been loaded for you.

Note: When you run your solution, you will see two warning messages about ignoring observations. These messages simply indicate that plotly is ignoring missing values.

  • Adapt the subplot() code to allow the x- and y-axis titles to be shared.
  • Add the title "User score vs. critic score by platform, 2016" to the plot.
# Add x-axis and y-axis labels, and a title
subplot(p1, p2, nrows = 2, shareX = T, shareY = T) %>%
   layout(title = "User score vs. critic score by platform, 2016")

Polishing axis titles

The axes in a subplot can be renamed using the layout() command, just like in a single plot; however, there are multiple x-axes to rename. For example, a 2 x 2 grid of plots requires four x-axis labels:

p %>% # subplot
   layout(
     xaxis = list(title = "title 1"), 
     xaxis2 = list(title = "title 2"),
     xaxis3 = list(title = "title 3"), 
     xaxis4 = list(title = "title 4")
   )

A similar strategy holds for the y-axis labels.

In this example, your task is to polish the axis titles on a subplot. Note that plotly has already been loaded for you.

  • For the first plot in sp2, use "Global Sales (M units)" for the y-axis label, and leave the x-axis label blank.
  • For the second plot in sp2, label the x-axis "Year" and the y-axis "Global Sales (M units)".
p1  <- vgsales %>%
  filter(Publisher %in% c("Nintendo", "Electronic Arts", "Activision",
                       "Sony Computer Entertainment", "Ubisoft")) %>%
  count(Publisher) %>%
  arrange(desc(n)) %>%
  head(5) %>%
  plot_ly(x = ~Publisher, y = ~n, color = ~Publisher) %>%
  add_bars()

p2 <- vgsales %>%
  filter(Publisher %in% c("Nintendo", "Electronic Arts", "Activision",
                       "Sony Computer Entertainment", "Ubisoft")) %>%
  group_by(Publisher, Year) %>%
  summarise(total_sales = n()) %>%
  plot_ly(x = ~Year, y =  ~total_sales, color = ~Publisher) %>%
  add_lines()
`summarise()` has grouped output by 'Publisher'. You can override using the
`.groups` argument.
